# Evaluation and significant experiments

Use this module when variants are compared, model behavior can regress, or quality claims will be shared.

Create one record for a baseline, a decision-relevant variant, a regression check, or a cited final run.
Do not record every trace. Detailed prompts, responses, spans, and metrics may remain in an external system
such as an experiment tracker or observability platform.

Each result should link a stable `run_id` to the relevant decision, code revision, dataset version,
model/configuration, metric definition, API usage, and evidence. Mark invalid and failed runs instead of
silently removing them.

Before publishing a result, verify that the protocol is comparable, the dataset may be referenced, the
metric was defined before interpretation, and limitations are explicit.

Define the protocol in `EVALUATION_PLAN.md` before interpreting results. Separate the development set used
for iteration from held-out validation, and document contamination risks. Include nominal, boundary,
adversarial, misuse, and important failure cases in proportion to product risk.

Use an acceptance threshold tied to an acceptance criterion, not the best observed run. Record sample size,
variance or uncertainty, exclusions, missing results, and error analysis. Aggregate metrics must not hide a
material failure for a user segment or critical case.

For human evaluation, define the rubric, reviewer qualification, disagreement handling, and exposure to
sensitive content. For model-based evaluation, record judge model/configuration, calibration evidence,
position or verbosity effects, and known judge bias. A judge score is evidence about a protocol, not ground
truth.
